    beginner: `Middle Ground Fallacy = Asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.`,
    detail: `Middle Ground Fallacy

Description:
In this question, the quoted claim is "Halfway between truth and lie is still a lie.".
That is asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.

Example (question)
« Halfway between truth and lie is still a lie. »

Example (everyday)
In a family conversation, someone makes the same mistake by asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.

Example (another context)
In a neighborhood discussion, the same error shows up when a person is asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth instead of checking the claim.

How it works
The argument uses a shortcut instead of real evidence.
It sounds settled because the speaker is asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.

So:
- The conclusion sounds stronger than the evidence.
- The real issue gets replaced by a shortcut.
- A quick answer takes the place of careful checking.

Key concept inside it
Middle Ground Fallacy:
Asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- It can hide the evidence the listener should be looking for.
- It can reward confidence, popularity, or emotion instead of proof.
- It can turn a useful discussion into a distraction.

The uncomfortable implication
A claim can feel convincing for the wrong reason.
The argument can still fail even when it feels obvious.

One-line version
Middle Ground Fallacy = Asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.`,
